From: PS4 Linux Baikal Port <noreply@ps4-linux>
Subject: [PATCH] drivers/ps4: fix bpcie demuxer in shared-vector mode

When the kernel boots with no IOMMU interrupt-remapping (which is the
production case on Baikal — ArabPixel's loader explicitly disables
the AMD-Vi IR before kexec), bpcie_assign_irqs() forces nvec=1 and
bpcie_msi_domain_set_desc() ORs 0x1F into msi_hwirq:

    arg->msi_hwirq |= 0x1F;     // shared mode: hwirq | 0x1F

So the *one* MSI vector that gets allocated for each PCI function
lands at hwirq 0x14XF (X is the function number).  No child virqs are
created at hwirq 0x14E0, 0x14E1, 0x14E2 etc.

But bpcie_handle_edge_irq() — the irq flow handler installed for
every virq in the bpcie MSI domain — does this on every interrupt
for functions 4 / 5 / 7:

    u32 initial_hwirq = desc->irq_data.hwirq & ~0x1fLL;   // 0x14E0
    ...
    for (i = 0; i < 32; i++) {
        if (subfunc_mask & (1 << i)) {
            unsigned int virq = irq_find_mapping(domain,
                                                 initial_hwirq + i);
            ...
            handle_edge_irq(new_desc);
        }
    }

In shared-vector mode there is NO virq mapped at initial_hwirq + i for
any i ≤ 4 (the only mapped virq is at initial_hwirq | 0x1F).  So every
iteration of the loop calls irq_find_mapping() that returns 0,
irq_to_desc(0) is essentially a no-op, and the dispatch silently does
nothing.  The xHCI command-completion MSI is **swallowed**, the
kernel waits TRB_RING_TIMEOUT (5 s) for the command, gives up, and
reports:

    xhci_aeolia 0000:00:14.7: Error while assigning device slot ID:
                              Command Aborted
    usb usb1-port1: couldn't allocate usb_device

This explains why USB device enumeration has been broken on every
6.x-Baikal port that doesn't run with IOMMU-IR enabled — and why
none of our previous patches (0005 settle delays, 0006 IRQ-via-apcie,
0007 imod_interval+caps retry) moved the symptom: they all stay on
the wrong code path because the demuxer never delivers anything.

Fix: detect shared-vector mode at the top of bpcie_handle_edge_irq()
by checking whether the hwirq has all-1s in the bottom 5 bits.  If
so, bypass the per-subfunc demux entirely and run the standard
handle_edge_irq() against the shared parent desc directly.  The
registered driver handler (xhci_irq, ahci_irq, ...) reads its own
status register to decide whether the interrupt was for it, exactly
the same way IRQF_SHARED interrupts work everywhere else in the
kernel.

Also handles funcs 5 (DMAC) and 4 (PCIE/glue/ICC) the same way.

Discovered 2026-05-09 by tracing the residual Command Aborted on
boot #10 (clean rebuild with all USB+IOMMU patches active).  The
"bpcie_assign_irqs returning 1" log line and matching-irq-number
output for both xHCI controllers were the smoking gun.

Signed-off-by: Meerzulee <17146298+meerzulee@users.noreply.github.com>
---
--- a/drivers/ps4/ps4-bpcie.c
+++ b/drivers/ps4/ps4-bpcie.c
@@ -214,6 +214,25 @@
 	//return handle_edge_irq(desc);
 	u32 func = (desc->irq_data.hwirq >> 5) & 7;
 	u32 initial_hwirq = desc->irq_data.hwirq & ~0x1fLL;
+
+	/*
+	 * Shared-vector mode: when bpcie_msi_domain_set_desc has OR'd 0x1F
+	 * into the hwirq (the no-IOMMU-IR fallback that allocates one MSI
+	 * vector per PCI function instead of one per subfunction), there
+	 * are NO child virqs for the per-subfunc demuxer below to dispatch
+	 * to.  initial_hwirq + i would resolve to nothing for every i in
+	 * the demux loop, so the xHCI command-completion MSI gets silently
+	 * swallowed and the kernel hits TRB_RING_TIMEOUT (5 s) →
+	 * "Error while assigning device slot ID: Command Aborted" on the
+	 * first ENABLE_SLOT.  Bypass the demux and run the standard edge
+	 * handler against the shared parent virq directly; the registered
+	 * driver handler (e.g. xhci_irq) will then read its own status
+	 * register to decide whether the IRQ was for it.
+	 */
+	if ((desc->irq_data.hwirq & 0x1f) == 0x1f) {
+		handle_edge_irq(desc);
+		return;
+	}
 	//sc_dbg("bpcie_handle_edge_irq(hwirq=0x%X, irq=0x%X)\n", vector, desc->irq_data.irq);
 	unsigned int vector_to_write;
 	unsigned int mask;
